  "opinion": "As a woman who’s been working in construction for over twenty years and raised three children while navigating life in New York, I’ve seen how the gender gap in science isn’t just a statistic—it’s a lived reality. When I first started in carpentry, I was told by mentors that ‘science is for boys,’ and that idea stuck with me long after I’d learned to build houses and bridges. The gap isn’t just about women being underrepresented in labs or universities; it’s about the cultural messages that tell girls they’re not built for precision, math, or problem-solving. My parents had different backgrounds—my mother never finished high school, but my father had a master’s degree—so I grew up knowing that education could open doors, but also that the world wasn’t always ready to welcome it. Now, as a self-employed carpenter who’s deeply depressed by the pace of life and the lack of connection, I see how the gender gap in science mirrors the isolation many feel. We need to address it, not by pushing girls into STEM fields like they’re a race to a finish line, but by creating spaces where curiosity isn’t punished. For example, community workshops that pair hands-on building with science experiments could help bridge the divide. It’s not about fixing people—it’s about changing the systems that tell us we don’t belong. And if we do that, maybe we’ll all learn to build something better together.",
